## Summary

The function `count_up_while(n) -> u64` has a trivial contract: no precondition, postcondition `result == n`, no failure modes (the loop terminates when `i == n`, so `i += 1` never overflows).

### Tests kept

| Test | Contract clause captured |
| --- | --- |
| `zero_returns_zero` | Boundary on input `n = 0` (loop body never executes) |
| `known_values` | Small concrete values ‚Äî catches off-by-one (`1`, `5`, `100`) |
| `returns_n` (proptest, `0..10_000`) | Main postcondition: `count_up_while(n) == n` |

### Tests removed as derived

- **`result_at_least_n`** (`result >= n`) ‚Äî strictly weaker than `returns_n`. Equality implies `>=`, so any implementation passing `returns_n` automatically passes this; any bug it would catch is already caught.
- **`result_at_most_n`** (`result <= n`) ‚Äî same reasoning; subsumed by the equality test.

### Tests considered but not added

- **Monotonicity** (`n1 <= n2 ‚üπ result1 <= result2`): a derived algebraic fact about the identity `result == n`, adds nothing.
- **Termination / no-panic check**: implicit ‚Äî proptest would already surface a panic.
- **Large `n` near `u64::MAX`**: skipped intentionally ‚Äî the loop is O(n) so this would take forever; the property `returns_n` is the same shape there as for small `n`, and verifying it at runtime gives no additional contract information.
